INSERT INTO `news` VALUES (2,'Peace FM Report on ARIS Samsung Room','2014-november-peace-fm-report-on-aris-samsung-room','','<p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2014/december/peace-fm-feature.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"470\" height=\"264\" /></p><p>Technology giant, Samsung Electronics West Africa (SEWA) has introduced its first Samsung School education solution to the Al Rayan International School, East-Legon.</p><p>The solution integrates an array of Samsung devices with interactive software to impart knowledge in students. Components of the Samsung School solution are Samsung-powered e-boards, server, Samsung tablets, wifi access point and a wifi printer</p><p><a href=\"http://news.peacefmonline.com/pages/tech/201412/224983.php\">Read the rest</a></p>','Technology giant, Samsung Electronics West Africa (SEWA) has introduced its first Samsung School education solution to the Al Rayan International School, East-Legon.The solution integrates an array of Samsung devices wit...','2014-11-19 18:57:24','2015-02-21 18:51:17','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2014-12-08 00:00:00'),(3,'Samsung Smart School in ARIS','2014-november-samsung-smart-school-in-aris','/img/uploads/2014/november/akwaba-annette-austin.jpg','<p>A video report on ARIS being the first school in Ghana to implement the Samsung Smart School platform</p><div class=\"videoWrapper\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/wi6NFVl6UK8\" width=\"420\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>','A video report on ARIS being the first school in Ghana to implement the Samsung Smart School platform','2014-11-19 18:59:58','2015-02-10 21:17:54','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2014-12-10 00:00:00'),(15,'What are the beliefs and values that drive the PYP ?','2015-february-what-are-the-beliefs-and-values-that-drive-the-pyp','','<p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/february/values-beliefs.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"431\" height=\"281\" /></p><p>In the PYP, it is believed that learning takes place best when it is connected to what is genuinely a component of the world around the student, not merely what is all too often contrived and then im- posed upon the student in school; that the acquisition of knowledge and skills and the search for meaning and understanding are best done in the context of the exploration of relevant content. PYP schools should provide students with learning experiences that are engaging, relevant, challenging and significant, in learning environments that are stimulating and provocative, where:</p><ul><li>adults are sensitive facilitators of the process of empowering students to value their learning and to take responsibility for it</li><li>students are seen as competent and are listened to</li><li>students are encouraged to be curious, be inquisitive, ask questions, explore and interact with the environment physically, socially and intellectually</li><li>explicit learning outcomes and the learning process are made transparent to the students</li><li>students are supported in their struggle for mastery and control on their journey to become in- dependent, autonomous learners</li><li>the learning experiences are differentiated to accommodate the range of abilities and learning styles in the group</li><li>the collaboration on the part of all the PYP teachers is high, and there is a commitment to the transdisciplinary model at the core of this programme of international education.</li></ul>','In the PYP, it is believed that learning takes place best when it is connected to what is genuinely a component of the world around the student, not merely what is all too often contrived and then im- posed upon the stud...','2015-02-07 12:40:02','2015-02-21 18:50:38','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-01-07 00:00:00'),(16,'Black Holes, an ASG Research Project','2015-february-black-holes-an-asg-research-project','','<p>Al-Rayan students Mouayad Toutoung (Year 11) and Bashhar Byrouthy (Year 10) produced a stirring video animation about the weird and wonderful topic of Black Holes! As members of the ASG (Astronomical Society of Ghana) the students meet monthly with other members to research and learn about Astronomy topics, and follow with a fruitful discussion. The meetings are held monthly at the <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/ghanaplanetarium\">Ghana Planetarium</a>.</p><p><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/T9nArucCJzc\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>','Al-Rayan students Mouayad Toutoung (Year 11) and Bashhar Byrouthy (Year 10) produced a stirring video animation about the weird and wonderful topic of Black Holes! As members of the ASG (Astronomical Society of Ghana) th...','2015-02-07 12:41:30','2015-03-20 10:33:38','news','dtoutoungi@aris.edu.gh','2015-01-07 00:00:00'),(17,'Lincoln CAS trips with students from ARIS','2015-february-lincoln-cas-trips-with-students-from-aris','','<p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2014/december/lcs_aris_cover.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"471\" height=\"278\" /></p><p>The LCS CAS program has taken service learning to another level by engaging a fellow IB school in Ghana on their CAS trips. The new initiative connects students from the two schools in joint CAS trips and encourages them to fundraise together towards a common goal.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://www.lincoln.edu.gh/page.cfm?p=487&amp;newsid=911\">Read the rest</a></p>','The LCS CAS program has taken service learning to another level by engaging a fellow IB school in Ghana on their CAS trips. The new initiative connects students from the two schools in joint CAS trips and encourages them...','2015-02-10 21:24:16','2015-02-21 18:50:56','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2014-12-12 00:00:00'),(18,'Accepting Disability: The School That Made All The Difference','2015-february-accepting-disability-the-school-that-made-all-the-difference','','<p><em><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/january/modern_ghana_logo.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"219\" height=\"114\" /></em></p><p><em>Modern Ghana</em> reports:</p><p>No institution worth its sort would turn a blind eye to a very compelling social responsibility which, hitherto, has been neglected or forgotten for the want of a softer statement to aptly put it. However, it is quite obfuscating to find out how apathetic society is towards the physically challenged and that is easily read in the general lack of provisions made in all aspects of life.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.modernghana.com/news/591052/1/accepting-disability-the-school-that-made-all-the-.html\">Read the rest</a></p>','Modern Ghana reports:No institution worth its sort would turn a blind eye to a very compelling social responsibility which, hitherto, has been neglected or forgotten for the want of a softer statement to aptly put it. Ho...','2015-02-10 21:27:29','2015-02-21 18:50:18','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-01-09 00:00:00'),(19,'​LCS collaborates with ARIS and National Forestry Commission to preserve wildlife','2015-february-lcs-collaborates-with-aris-and-national-forestry-commission-to-preserve-wildlife','','<p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/january/aris_linconln_collaboration.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>LCS teachers, Barbara Bilgre and Eric Boateng, are spearheading a wildlife and environmental preservation project with their students in collaboration with the Forestry Commission of Ghana and Al Rayyan International School (ARIS), another IB school in Accra.</p><p>LCS CAS students will be partnering with ARIS CAS students on this community development project for the Solo Monkey Forest, as well as on smaller service projects.</p><p>Students from the two schools met at ARIS premises in East Legon for their first meeting to discuss the proposed monkey sanctuary initiative.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.lincoln.edu.gh/page.cfm?p=487&amp;newsid=934&amp;ncat=3\">Read the rest</a></p>','LCS teachers, Barbara Bilgre and Eric Boateng, are spearheading a wildlife and environmental preservation project with their students in collaboration with the Forestry Commission of Ghana and Al Rayyan International Sch...','2015-02-10 21:40:22','2015-02-21 18:50:03','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-01-30 00:00:00'),(20,'Visit to Silver Star Automotives as Part of Unit of Inquiry','2015-february-visit-to-silver-star-automotives-as-part-of-unit-of-inquiry','','<h3>How we Organize ourselves</h3><p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Central Idea:</strong></span> Communities make effort to create transportation systems to meet their needs.</p><p>(details after photos)</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/february/mercedes-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/february/mercedes-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/february/wara-malek.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/february/mercedes-4.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p><strong>Features of transportation, decisions involved in using transportation and how systems of transportation respond to changing needs</strong> are the <strong>lines of inquiry</strong> year one students where inquiring about. Questions arose about do we get from one place to another? What are the different types of transportation experienced? These provocations provided students with a solid grounding for inquiring into the types of transport communities develop and how the needs of a community can influence the mode of transport within the community.</p><p>Throughout the unit, we had the opportunity to inquire into a system that has evolved into a range of ways overtime and varies across locations. They inquired into transport on land, sea and air for both people and cargo. Moreover, they further visited Silver Star Motors. The purpose was acquainting themselves with the various types of vehicles. They watched video presentations on the process of making of Mercedes Benz, cars and trucks. Moreover, We invited <a href=\"http://ghana.westafrican-rescue.com/\">WARA</a> to our campus and a paramedic explained to students the procedures in taking care of a sick or wounded person. Learners were exposed to the ambulance and inspected the different parts and tools; nevertheless asked lots of questions they were wondering about.</p><p><a href=\"http://silverstar.com.gh/News-And-Events/Local/A-Visit-by-Al-Rayaan-International-School.aspx\">More at&nbsp;Silver Star\'s website</a></p>','How we Organize ourselvesCentral Idea: Communities make effort to create transportation systems to meet their needs.(details after photos)Features of transportation, decisions involved in using transportation and how sys...','2015-02-13 19:35:32','2015-02-27 18:17:35','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-02-13 00:00:00'),(21,'Ghana\'s Independence Day in ARIS','2015-march-ghanas-independence-day-in-aris','','<p class=\"p1\">Independence Day Celebrations in ARIS saw an array of colourful activities. A day when the entire school rose above personal interests to put Ghana first and celebrate an achievement, which distinguished our motherland 58 years ago. It all started with an enthralling presentation themed, &ldquo;Ghana&rsquo;s Journey to Independence&rdquo; during morning assembly, which offered students the opportunity to find out about events that transpired during the colonial rule in Ghana&rsquo;s history.</p><p class=\"p1\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_07.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p class=\"p2\">Students of all nationalities were elegantly dressed in Ghanaian traditional clothing to symbolise the preservation of the rich Ghanaian culture in our school and to remember the struggles of our forefathers and their relentless efforts that have made it possible to celebrate this important day.</p><p class=\"p2\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_02.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p class=\"p2\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_08.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p class=\"p2\">&ldquo;Ghana&rdquo; was the talk of the day through teaching, classroom and break-time discussions while merriments continued through out the day with an abundance of picture-taking and story-telling as we braced for a week-long celebration.</p><p class=\"p2\">FROM ARIS, WE SAY &ldquo;AYEKOO GHANA&rdquo; !</p><p class=\"p2\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_05.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p class=\"p2\">&nbsp;</p><p class=\"p2\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_04.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p class=\"p2\"><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/ghana_day/ghana_day_09.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p>','Independence Day Celebrations in ARIS saw an array of colourful activities. A day when the entire school rose above personal interests to put Ghana first and celebrate an achievement, which distinguished our motherland 5...','2015-03-06 20:32:08','2015-03-18 08:42:01','news','dtoutoungi@aris.edu.gh','2015-03-06 00:00:00'),(22,'Celebrating Pi Day!','2015-march-celebrating-pi-day','','<p>In what many consider the highlight of the year, ARIS Secondary school students celebrated <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi_Day\">international Pi Day</a>&nbsp;with their teachers.&nbsp;If one day of the year screams &ldquo;Party&rdquo; in our school, that day is March 14. Each year, the Mathematics Department gathers a collection of ideas and activities that will help plan the Pi Day from all Departments, and the school takes a break from the normal routine to celebrate Pi.</p><p>The event included Pi-ing teachers, word games and field activities with items that have circle shapes (Cakes, Doughnuts, hoops..) The money raised went to the math department for research and getting more resources.</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/pi%20day/pi_day_05.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/pi%20day/pi_day_08.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>This year&rsquo;s Pi Day is not an ordinary one. It is in fact, an epic Pi Day on 3.14.15 at 9.26.53. This date and time corresponds to the first 10 digits of Pi (&pi; = 3.141592653). Incidentally, this happens once every century, which makes this one truly a once-in-a-lifetime event. The next Pi Day will be in 100 years.</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/pi%20day/pi_day_09.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/pi%20day/pi_day_10.JPG\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>Pi has a gazillion-and-one uses in everyday life. Therefore, the events are planned to engage our pupils and the community in the fun of experimental learning as a way to inspire the next generation of scientists, researchers, medical practitioners and educators who will drive life changing innovation. It is used to calculate the circumferences and areas of circle, and has many applications in Physics, Engineering, Genetics, Ecological changes and Global Warming. But it appears &lsquo;behind the scenes&rsquo; in just countless ways across many disciplines.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>','In what many consider the highlight of the year, ARIS Secondary school students celebrated international Pi Day&nbsp;with their teachers.&nbsp;If one day of the year screams &ldquo;Party&rdquo; in our school, that day is...','2015-03-14 09:08:06','2015-03-20 08:45:50','news','dtoutoungi@aris.edu.gh','2015-03-14 00:00:00'),(23,'ARIS Wins Fun Run','2015-march-aris-wins-fun-run','','<p>A few hundred people took part in the fifth edition of the Family Fun Run event organised by Happy Fm and Lakeside Marina, in Accra. The Family Fun Run is a family event held annually on Independence Day to encourage healthy living.<br />Family Fun Run participants met their match, running against a team of ARIS Secondary Students (Mouayad Toutoungi, Omar Farouk, Bashhar Byrouthy, Karim Beiruti, Hauwa Ibrahim Aminu. The students arrived in Medina at 5:30 am ready to run the grueling six-kilometers.</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/fun%20run/fun_run_2015.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>The runners were proud of the outcome, taking home the trophy for Fastest School in the 13 &ndash; 18 age category. The team also won a Cannon printer/copier for ARIS. &nbsp;</p>','A few hundred people took part in the fifth edition of the Family Fun Run event organised by Happy Fm and Lakeside Marina, in Accra. The Family Fun Run is a family event held annually on Independence Day to encourage hea...','2015-03-18 08:56:51','2015-03-18 10:31:39','news','dtoutoungi@aris.edu.gh','2015-03-18 00:00:00'),(26,'CAS SOLO MONKEY SANCTUARY ','2015-march-cas-solo-monkey-sanctuary','','<p>The Solo Forest Monkey Sanctuary is one hour from ARIS in Old Bortianor, the Kokrobite Area. The area is not only covered with Wawa, Odum and Sapele Mohagany trees but is home to approximately 70 Mona and Spot Nosed monkeys, butterflies, birds and reptiles. The Solo Spring originates from a nearby highland and runs through the forest which gathers in a pool and serves as the main source of water for the inhabitants. Under law poachers are prohibited to hunt. The 30 acre sanctuary is under tremendous threat from real estate encroachers. <br />ARIS students from Year 7-11 and a few friends from LCS, along with the guide are fighting to save the animals and the remaining 30 acres of the 100 acres, as well as, create awareness about environmental issues in the area and throughout Ghana. On this particular trip, students engaged in tree planting, a cleanup of surrounding areas and construction of two simple footbridges across the natural stream.</p>','The Solo Forest Monkey Sanctuary is one hour from ARIS in Old Bortianor, the Kokrobite Area. The area is not only covered with Wawa, Odum and Sapele Mohagany trees but is home to approximately 70 Mona and Spot Nosed monk...','2015-03-20 10:19:00','2015-03-20 10:20:00','news','dtoutoungi@aris.edu.gh','2014-11-22 00:00:00'),(25,'Inquiry and the School Librarian','2015-march-inquiry-and-the-school-librarian','','<p>ARIS librarian Katie, recently had the opportunity to go participate in an IB Librarian training at the AISA Conference in early March of 2015. This was an incredible opportunity to meet and collaborate with other librarians in Africa along with it being set in beautiful Cape Town, South Africa. The three day conference was packed with interactive sessions with the facilitator Dawn Rutland, who is a certified IB trainer at St. Johns International School in Waterloo, Belgium.</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/Inquiry%20and%20the%20school%20librarian/IMG_20150307_151412458.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>Many topics were covered, a few included: cycle of inquiry, academic honesty, library resources, OPACs, e-book platforms, and the learner profile. Katie found the workshop unique in the way that it spanned the three IB Programmes and had a big emphasis on international resources for students around the world. Katie gained a sense that many of concepts in the IB overlapped in the area of international mindedness. Culminating projects, Mother tongue resources, multiple language courses, made it clear that the IB Programme is striving for a way of exploring, researching, and looking at the world in a way that other school programmes do not.</p><p><img src=\"/img/uploads/news/2015/march/Inquiry%20and%20the%20school%20librarian/IMG_20150307_151447311.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>Katie was endeared to Dawn and the two other women in her training for being open minded, kind, and honest about the obstacles that librarians have. The training emphasized the importance of having face-to-face conversations with other librarians who can understand and help each other over the hurdles. Katie hopes she can give to ARIS what Dawn and AISA gave to her, which is the opportunity to be a teacher and learner at the same time.</p>','ARIS librarian Katie, recently had the opportunity to go participate in an IB Librarian training at the AISA Conference in early March of 2015. This was an incredible opportunity to meet and collaborate with other librar...','2015-03-20 10:07:11','2015-03-21 11:52:03','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-03-20 00:00:00'),(27,'Teaching and Learning through Inquiry Workshop','2015-march-teaching-and-learning-through-inquiry-workshop','','<p>ARIS PYP Teachers enjoyed an exciting and engaging In-School Workshop on Teaching and Learning through Inquiry, by Lucy Elliott, coming from a PYP school in Uganda.</p><p>The workshop focused on the 21st Century Teaching and Learning approach which is based on Inquiry.<br />It highlighted Kath Murdoch and Kathy Short Inquiry Cycles, as well as the techniques, strategies, activities, etc. that should take place in an Inquiry setting where the pupils become independent learners with curiosity to go beyond information and experience to seek an explanation, to ask why and to consider what if.</p>','ARIS PYP Teachers enjoyed an exciting and engaging In-School Workshop on Teaching and Learning through Inquiry, by Lucy Elliott, coming from a PYP school in Uganda.The workshop focused on the 21st Century Teaching and Le...','2015-03-20 10:51:22','2015-03-23 22:15:48','news','mustapha.hamoui@gmail.com','2015-03-07 00:00:00');
